Great framing. Based on your parameters, here’s the technical call:

Your current project constraints explicitly say DynamoDB is the source of truth in system-context.md, plus cost target under $10/client/month and “do not introduce new services.”

Quick option scorecard (for your criteria)

| Option | Cost | Security | Integration into current workflow | Exportable to humans | Ecosystem integrations |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| DynamoDB (current stack) | Best | Best (IAM-native, no server patching) | Best (already in Lambda/Terraform flow) | Good (export to S3/CSV) | Good (Zapier/n8n/Airtable via API/Lambda) |
| Small EC2 + Postgres/MySQL | Worse (instance + storage + ops) | Riskier (OS hardening, patching, backups, network mgmt) | Medium/low (new infra + ops overhead) | Good | Good |
| Airtable as primary DB | Medium/high at scale | Medium (SaaS permissions model) | Medium (would re-architect backend flow) | Best | Best |
| RDS/Aurora Serverless | Medium/high | Strong | Medium (new service + migrations) | Good | Good |

Recommendation

1. Keep DynamoDB as primary booking record store now.
2. Add human-friendly exports as a separate path:
- DynamoDB -> scheduled export (or Lambda transform) -> S3 CSV/JSON
- Optional sync job to Airtable for ops visibility
3. Add integration layer (not DB swap):
- Webhook/event relay for Zapier/n8n
- Clean API endpoints for AI agents/LLMs
4. Defer CloudWatch->S3 archival until pricing engine ships (your current sequencing is right).

Why this is the best fit for your criteria

1. Lowest operational burden and lowest failure surface.
2. Strongest security posture with least custom work.
3. Zero architecture churn in your existing Lambda/API/Terraform workflow.
4. Still gives you “human hands” export via S3 CSV/JSON and optional Airtable mirror.
5. Keeps future integrations open without changing your system of record.

